<exercises>
  <title>Exercises</title>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-ccsol-1">
  <title>Characteristic Equation</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      What is the characteristic equation associated with the differential equation  
      <m>y'' - 6y' + 8y = 0</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement><p><m>r^{2} - 6r + 8 = 0</m></p></statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The characteristic equation comes from substituting <m>y=e^{rx}</m> and dividing by 
          <m>e^{rx}</m>. 
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>r^{2} + 6r + 8 = 0</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Sign error: the coefficient of <m>y'</m> is <m>-6</m>, not <m>+6</m>.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>r - 6 + 8 = 0</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>This omits the quadratic term required for a second-order equation.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-ccsol-2">
  <title>Distinct Real Roots</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      The characteristic equation <m>r^{2} - 5r + 6 = 0</m> has distinct real roots.  
      What is the general solution of the corresponding ODE <m>y'' - 5y' + 6y = 0</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>y = C_{1} e^{2x} + C_{2} e^{3x}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The roots are <m>r=2</m> and <m>r=3</m>. Distinct real roots yield  
          <m>y=C_{1}e^{r_{1}x}+C_{2}e^{r_{2}x}</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = C_{1}e^{5x} + C_{2}e^{6x}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Incorrect: those are not the roots of the quadratic.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = C_{1}\cos x + C_{2}\sin x</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>This form is for complex roots, not real distinct roots.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-ccsol-3">
  <title>Checking a Proposed Solution</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Does <m>y = e^{4x}</m> solve the ODE <m>y'' - 8y' + 16y = 0</m>?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p>Yes, because <m>y'' - 8y' + 16y = (16e^{4x}) - 8(4e^{4x}) + 16e^{4x} = 0</m>.</p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. This ODE corresponds to the characteristic polynomial  
          <m>(r-4)^{2}=0</m>, whose root <m>r=4</m> matches <m>e^{4x}</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>No, because <m>y'' - 8y' + 16y = 8e^{4x}</m>.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Re-check the derivatives and the coefficients.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p>No, because <m>e^{4x}</m> only solves first-order equations.</p></statement>
      <feedback><p>Incorrect—exponentials are standard solutions for constant-coefficient ODEs.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-ccsol-4">
  <title>Repeated Root Case</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      If the characteristic equation has a repeated root <m>r</m>, what is the correct form of the 
      general solution?
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>y = C_{1} e^{rx} + C_{2} \, x e^{rx}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. When the characteristic root is repeated, the second 
          solution is <m>x e^{rx}</m>.  
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = C_{1} e^{rx} + C_{2} e^{-rx}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>This form corresponds to distinct real or complex roots, not repeated roots.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = C_{1} + C_{2}e^{rx}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>No—this omits the necessary <m>x e^{rx}</m> term.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="mcq-ccsol-5">
  <title>Solving a Constant-Coefficient ODE</title>

  <statement>
    <p>
      Solve the ODE <m>y'' + 4y' + 4y = 0</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>

  <choices randomize="yes">

    <choice correct="yes">
      <statement>
        <p><m>y = C_{1} e^{-2x} + C_{2} x e^{-2x}</m></p>
      </statement>
      <feedback>
        <p>
          Correct. The characteristic equation <m>(r+2)^{2}=0</m> has repeated root <m>r=-2</m>, so the 
          solution is <m>C_{1}e^{-2x} + C_{2} x e^{-2x}</m>.
        </p>
      </feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = C_{1}e^{-2x} + C_{2}e^{2x}</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>This corresponds to two distinct real roots, which is not the case here.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

    <choice>
      <statement><p><m>y = C_{1}\cos 2x + C_{2}\sin 2x</m></p></statement>
      <feedback><p>This corresponds to complex roots, not a repeated negative real root.</p></feedback>
    </choice>

  </choices>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ccsol-ivp-particular-homogeneous">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the IVP
    </p>
    <me>
      y'' - 2y' + 2y = 2x, 
      \qquad 
      y(0)=4, \quad y'(0)=8.
    </me>

    <ol marker="(a)">
      <li><p>Show that <m>y_p(x) = x + 1</m> solves the differential equation.</p></li>

      <li><p>Verify that <m>y_1(x)=e^{x}\cos x</m> and <m>y_2(x)=e^{x}\sin x</m> solve the associated homogeneous equation.</p></li>

      <li><p>Use (a) and (b) to find a solution to the IVP.</p></li>
    </ol>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <ol marker="(a)">

      <li>
        <p>
          For <m>y_p = x+1</m>, we compute:
        </p>
        <me>
          y_p' = 1, y_p'' = 0.
        </me>
        <p>Insert into the ODE:</p>
        <md>
          <mrow> y_p'' - 2y_p' + 2y_p 
          \amp = 0 - 2(1) + 2(x+1) </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = -2 + 2x + 2 </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = 2x. </mrow>
        </md>
        <p>
          Hence <m>y_p</m> is indeed a particular solution.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          For <m>y_1(x)=e^{x}\cos x</m>:
        </p>
        <me>
          y_1' = e^{x}(\cos x - \sin x),\\
          y_1'' = e^{x}(\!-2\sin x).
        </me>
        <p>Substitute into the homogeneous equation <m>y'' - 2y' + 2y = 0</m>:</p>
        <md>
          <mrow> y_1'' - 2y_1' + 2y_1 
          \amp = e^{x}(-2\sin x)
          - 2e^{x}(\cos x - \sin x)
          + 2e^{x}\cos x </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = 0. </mrow>
        </md>

        <p>
          For <m>y_2(x)=e^{x}\sin x</m>:
        </p>
        <me>
          y_2' = e^{x}(\sin x + \cos x),\\
          y_2'' = e^{x}(2\cos x).
        </me>

        <p>Substitute:</p>
        <md>
          <mrow> y_2'' - 2y_2' + 2y_2
          \amp = e^{x}(2\cos x) 
          - 2e^{x}(\sin x + \cos x)
          + 2e^{x}\sin x </mrow>
          <mrow> \amp = 0. </mrow>
        </md>

        <p>
          Thus both <m>y_1</m> and <m>y_2</m> solve the homogeneous equation.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          The general solution is:
        </p>
        <md>
          <mrow> y(x) \amp = y_p(x) + C_1 y_1(x) + C_2 y_2(x) </mrow>
          <mrow>  \amp   = (x+1) + C_1 e^{x}\cos x + C_2 e^{x}\sin x. </mrow>
        </md>

        <p>Apply the initial conditions.</p>
        <p><strong>First:</strong></p>
        <me>
          y(0) = 1 + C_1 = 4 
          \quad\Rightarrow\quad C_1 = 3.
        </me>

        <p><strong>Next compute </strong> <m>y'</m>:</p>
        <me>
          y' = 1 
              + C_1 e^{x}(\cos x - \sin x)
              + C_2 e^{x}(\sin x + \cos x).
        </me>

        <p>Evaluate at <m>x=0</m>:</p>
        <me>
          y'(0) = 1 + C_1 + C_2 = 8.
        </me>
        <p>
          Using <m>C_1=3</m> gives:
        </p>
        <me>
          1 + 3 + C_2 = 8 \quad\Longrightarrow\quad C_2 = 4.
        </me>

        <p>
          Therefore, the solution to the IVP is:
        </p>
        <me>
          y(x) = x + 1 + 3 e^{x}\cos x + 4 e^{x}\sin x.
        </me>
      </li>

    </ol>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ccsol-general-solution-6-13">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Find the general solution to the differential equation
      <me>
        y'' + 6y' + 13y = 0.
      </me>
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      The characteristic equation is
    </p>
    <me>
      r^{2} + 6r + 13 = 0.
    </me>

    <p>
      Thus the roots are
    </p>
    <me>
      r = \frac{-6 \pm \sqrt{-16}}{2}
        = -3 \pm 2i.
    </me>

    <p>
      So the general solution is
    </p>

    <me>
      y(x) = e^{-3x}\bigl(C_1 \cos 2x + C_2 \sin 2x\bigr).
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ccsol-construct-ode">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Construct a differential equation whose general solution is
      <me>
        y = C_{1} e^{-2x}\cos(3x) \;+\; C_{2} e^{-2x}\sin(3x).
      </me>
    </p>
  </statement>

  <solution>
    <p>
      This solution corresponds to characteristic roots 
      <m>r = -2 \pm 3i</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Therefore the characteristic equation is
    </p>

    <me>
      (r + 2 - 3i)(r + 2 + 3i)
      = (r + 2)^{2} + 9
      = r^{2} + 4r + 13.
    </me>

    <p>
      Hence the corresponding differential equation is
    </p>

    <me>
      y'' + 4y' + 13y = 0.
    </me>
  </solution>
</exercise>

</exercises>

</section>

<section xml:id="sec-Advancedlearningobjectives22">
  <title>Advanced learning objectives</title>

    <p>
      In addition to mastering the basic objectives, here are the tasks you should be able 
          to perform, with practice:
    </p>

    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Construct the full general solution for each root type and understand why these functions are 
          linearly independent.   
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Apply initial conditions to solve for unknown constants using algebraic or matrix methods.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Interpret the mathematical structure of solutions in applications such as mechanical or 
          electrical systems, building intuition for later modeling chapters.
        </p>
      </li>

    </ul>

</section>


</handout>